On the accompanying diagram, note that the subclavian artery becomes the axillary artery as it passes into the axilla. As it then passes from the axilla into the anterior compartment of the arm, it becomes the brachial artery. Note also that the brachial artery gives one major branch in the arm, the deep brachial artery, which passes posterior to the humerus into the posterior compartment of the arm.
The brachial plexus prosection you have been given may, or may not, have the axillary artery.
